04156nam a2200445Ia 9780774853811DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20071992xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748538117 a10.59962/97807748538112doi  a(DE-B1597)691095  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.N79bD53 1992eb 7aPOL0200002bisacsh04a971.9/031 aDickerson, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhose North? :bPolitical Change, Political Development, and Self Government in the Northwest Territories /cMark Dickerson. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps, Figures, and Tables -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Political Change, Political Development, and the Crisis of Legitimacy -- t2 Geography, Demography, Economy, and Cultures -- t3 Formulating Process and Policies: The Historical Dimension, 1920-50 -- t4 Changing Policies, Not the Process: The Colonial Legacy, 1950-67 -- t5 Changing the Political Process of the Northwest Territories, 1967-79 -- t6 A More Autonomous Government of the Northwest Territories, 1979-91 -- t7 Self-Government and Political Development in the Northwest Territories -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Northwest Territories, which comprises one-third of Canada's land mass, is in many ways a distinct region -- more than just a vast storehouse of resources, the territories are home to a diverse population, the majority Natives who possess deep-seated cultures which have endured despite the pervasive influence of the dominant culture to the south. Residents of the Northwest Territories today face a number of difficult political issues: land claims, division of the territories, constitutional development, self-government, an accord for sharing resource revenues, and the establishment of their place within the Canadian federation. Whose North? provides the context for a better understanding of these issues and traces the evolution of an innovative, increasingly indigenous, governmental process. Today, eighteen of the twenty-four legislators are Native and the non-partisan, consensus style of government is unique in Canada. Mark Dickerson points out that within the NWT there is no unanimity on the nature of the system of government. He addresses the political tension between those advocating the continuation of a centralized government and those preferring a more decentralized form, particularly self-government, which many northerners view as the only way of preserving their culture. In many ways, the Northwest Territories is a test case and one of the most important social issues to be faced by Canadians in the twenty-first century. For Natives, it may determine whether they can indeed live in two cultures. Dickerson's depiction of the development of the territorial government and his discussion of the tension surrounding the choice of government will provide Canadians with an opportunity to begin to understand just what is at stake in this critical process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / State.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485381140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774853811423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774853811/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles